terDto` into a SQL condition.\n   - Validates if `defaultCompare` is set for the filter. If not, it throws an error.\n   - Depending on the `defaultCompare` value (like `e`, `ne`, `gt`, `lt`, etc.), it constructs a SQL condition and the corresponding value is converted to the appropriate JavaScript type via `convertDefaultValueToJsType()` and pushed into the `params` array for SQL parameterization.\n   - Returns the constructed SQL part for the given filter.\n\n3. **`convertDefaultValueToJsType()`**:\n   - Another private function that converts the default value from the filter to its corresponding JavaScript type based on the `sqlType` (e.g., converting `\"varchar\"` to a string and `\"int\"` to a number).\n   - Throws errors if the `defaultValue` is `undefined` or if an unknown SQL type is encountered.\n\n### Error Handling\n\n- Throughout the code, various checks are in place to ensure that properties (like `defaultCompare` and `defaultValue`) are defined. Descriptive errors are thrown to help diagnose issues when invalid states or unexpected values are encountered.\n\n### Summary\n\nIn conclusion, the `ListLogic.ts` file serves as a part of a backend that dynamically builds SQL queries based on user-defined filters and retrieves data accordingly. It ensures type safety and minimizes SQL injection risks by using parameterized queries. The structure allows for easy extension of filter types and SQL conditions.","refusal":null}]'),
