eading level={2}>Clone GIT Repo</Heading>\n                <Form>\n                    <Field label=\"GIT URL\"><Input /></Field>\n                    <FlexRow gap=\"1em\">\n                        <Button label=\"Process\" />\n                    </FlexRow>\n                </Form>\n\n                <Heading level={2}>Fine Tune</Heading>\n                <Form>\n                    <Field label=\"Name\"><Input /></Field>\n                    <FlexRow gap=\"1em\">\n                        <Button label=\"Execute\" />\n                    </FlexRow>\n                </Form>\n            </Navigation>\n        );\n    }\n}\n\nwindow.onload = () => {\n    const element = document.getElementById(''root'');\n    const root = createRoot(element);\n    root.render(<Page />)\n};\nwindow.onpageshow = (event) => {\n    if (event.persisted) {\n        window.location.reload();\n    }\n};\n```\n\nPlease update the input file so that when a file is attached, we save that file into ../temp folder."},{"role":"assistant","content":"Certainly! If you want to handle file uploads in Express without using `multer`, you can do it using the built-in `fs` module and the `body-parser` middleware. However, note that `multer` is often used because it simplifies file uploads, handling things like multipart form data easily. \n\nWhen not using `multer`, you need to manually parse the incoming request. For this example, we''ll be using the `busboy` library, which will help with parsing multipart form data. \n\n### Step 1: Install the Required Packages\n\nFirst, you need to install the `busboy` package along with Express (if you haven''t already):\n\n```bash\nnpm install express busboy\n```\n\n### Step 2: Set Up the Express Server\n\nHereâ€™s how you can set up your server to handle file uploads without using `multer`:\n\n```javascript\nconst express = require(''express'');\nconst fs = require(''fs'');\nconst path = require(''path'');\nconst Busboy = require(''busboy'');\n\nconst app = express();\nconst PORT = 3000;\n\n// Create upload route\napp.post(''/upload'', (req, res) => {\n    const busboy = new Busboy({ headers: req.headers });\n\n    busboy.on(''file'', (fieldname, file, filename, encoding, mimetype) => {\n        const saveTo = path.join(__dirname, ''../temp'', filename); // Save to ../temp\n\n        // Create a write stream to save the file\n        const writeStream = fs.createWriteStream(saveTo);\n        file.pipe(writeStream);\n\n        writeStream.on(''finish'', () => {\n            console.log(''File uploaded successfully:'', filename);\n            res.status(200).send(''File uploaded successfully.'');\n        });\n\n        writeStream.on(''error'', (err) => {\n            console.error(''Error uploading file:'', err);\n            res.status(500).send(''Error uploading file.'');\n        });\n    });\n\n    busboy.on(''finish'', () => {\n        console.log(''Upload complete'');\n    });\n\n    req.pipe(busboy);\n});\n\n// Start the server\napp.listen(PORT, () => {\n    console.log(`Server is running on http://localhost:${PORT}`);\n});\n```\n\n### Explanation of the Code:\n\n1. **Busboy Initialization**: We create a new instance of Busboy, passing the request headers to it.\n2. **File Event**: We listen to the `file` event, which is emitted for each file uploaded. We set the path where the file will be saved and create a write stream to save the file.\n3. **Piping the File Stream**: We pipe the incoming file stream to the write stream, which handles the file saving.\n4. **Finish and Error Handlers**: We set up handlers for when the file finishes writing and if thereâ€™s an error.\n5. **Finish Event**: We listen to the `finish` event to know when all fields have been processed.\n\n### Step 3: Update Your React Code\n\nMake sure your React code is as follows (the previous code I provided works fine):\n\n```javascript\n// React component code remains the same as provided earlier\n```\n\n### Important Notes:\n\n- Ensure the directory `../temp` exists, or you need to create it beforehand. You can add logic to create the directory if it doesn''t exist.\n- Proper error handling and validation should be implemented based on your requirements.\n- This setup also requires CORS handling if the client and server are on different origins.\n\nBy following these steps, you now have a basic file upload setup in Express without using `multer`. The file will be saved in the specified directory when uploaded from your React application.","refusal":null}]'),
