S_PASSWORD=postgres`: Sets the password for the default user to \"postgres\".\n  - `-e POSTGRES_DB=postgres`: Creates a default database named \"postgres\".\n\n- `-p 5432:5432`: Maps port 5432 on the host to port 5432 on the container. This allows local applications to connect to the PostgreSQL database running inside the container.\n\n- `-v $(pwd)/data:/var/lib/postgresql/data`: This option mounts the `data` directory in the current working directory into the container at `/var/lib/postgresql/data`. This is where PostgreSQL stores its database files, ensuring that data persists even if the container is stopped or removed.\n\n- `-d`: This runs the container in detached mode, meaning it runs in the background.\n\n- `postgres`: This specifies the image to use. In this case, it pulls the official PostgreSQL image from the container registry.\n\n### Summary\nIn summary, this script sets up a PostgreSQL database within a Podman container. It removes any existing data, creates a new data directory for storing the database files, and then launches a PostgreSQL container configured with a default user, password, and database. The data persists on the host file system thanks to the volume mapping, allowing for data reuse between container sessions.","refusal":null}]'),
