s that if no value is provided for this column during an insert, it will automatically be set to FALSE.\n\n### 2. Adding a Unique Constraint\n\n```sql\nALTER TABLE \"groups\" ADD CONSTRAINT \"uk_groups_display_name\" UNIQUE (\"display_name\");\n```\n\n- **ALTER TABLE \"groups\"**: This statement modifies the existing \"groups\" table.\n\n- **ADD CONSTRAINT \"uk_groups_display_name\"**: Here, a new constraint is being added. Constraints are rules that restrict the data that can be entered into a table.\n\n- **UNIQUE (\"display_name\")**: This part of the statement specifies that the \"display_name\" column must contain unique values. This means that no two rows in the \"groups\" table can have the same value in the \"display_name\" column, preventing duplication.\n\n### Summary\n\nIn summary, the provided file sets up a \"groups\" table that:\n\n- Has a primary key (`guid`) of type UUID.\n- Includes a `display_name` which cannot be null and must be unique for each group.\n- Contains a boolean column `is_administrator` that defaults to FALSE if not specified.\n\nThis structure is typically used in applications where groups (such as user roles or categories) have unique identifiers and names, and where it is necessary to keep track of whether a group has administrative privileges.","refusal":null}]'),
