lements jwt.JwtPayload {\n    public static expiresIn = \"1h\";\n    public static audience = \"lagovistatech.com\";\n    public static issuer = \"lagovistatech.com\";\n    public static subject = \"jwt_token\";\n    public static algorithm: \"RS512\" = \"RS512\";\n\n    public data: any;\n\n    public constructor(data: any = undefined) {\n        this.data = data;\n    }\n```\n- The `JwtToken` class implements the `jwt.JwtPayload` interface, which ensures that it conforms to the expected structure of a JWT payload.\n- Several static properties are defined:\n  - `expiresIn`: How long the token is valid (1 hour).\n  - `audience`: The intended recipient of the token, set to \"lagovistatech.com\".\n  - `issuer`: The entity that issued the token, also set to \"lagovistatech.com\".\n  - `subject`: The subject of the token, here labeled as \"jwt_token\".\n  - `algorithm`: The signing algorithm used, specified as \"RS512\".\n- An instance property `data` is included, which can hold any data associated with the token.\n\n### Constructor\n```typescript\npublic constructor(data: any = undefined) {\n    this.data = data;\n}\n```\n- The constructor allows an instance of `JwtToken` to be initialized with some data (defaults to `undefined` if not provided).\n\n### Method: sign\n```typescript\npublic sign(privateKey: string): string {\n    return jwt.sign({ data: this.data }, privateKey, {\n        expiresIn: JwtToken.expiresIn,\n        audience: JwtToken.audience,\n        issuer: JwtToken.issuer,\n        subject: JwtToken.subject,\n        algorithm: JwtToken.algorithm,\n        jwtid: UUIDv4.generate()\n    });\n}\n```\n- The `sign` method takes a `privateKey` as an argument and creates a JWT using the `jwt.sign()` method.\n- The payload includes the `data` property, and various options are provided, such as expiration time, audience, issuer, subject, algorithm, and a unique identifier (JWT ID) generated by `UUIDv4.generate()`.\n- The result of `jwt.sign()` is a string representation of the signed JWT.\n\n### Static Method: verify\n```typescript\npublic static verify(token: string, publicKey: string) {\n    const obj = jwt.verify(token, publicKey);\n\n    const ret = new JwtToken();\n    Object.assign(ret, obj);\n\n    return ret;\n}\n```\n- The `verify` static method takes a `token` and a `publicKey`, verifying the tokenâ€™s integrity and signature.\n- The `jwt.verify()` method returns the decoded payload, which is used to create a new instance of `JwtToken`.\n- The `Object.assign()` method copies the verified properties back onto the new `JwtToken` instance, allowing access to the payload''s data.\n\n### Summary\nIn essence, this `JwtToken` class provides a structured way to generate and verify JWTs in a TypeScript application, managing key aspects like expiration, audience, issuer, and algorithm. It encapsulates the functionality of JWT operations, promoting reusable and maintainable code while leveraging the capabilities of the `jsonwebtoken` library.","refusal":null}]'),
